PACKAGE WAS TRANSITING THROUGH HONG KONG FROM GUAM TO THE USA WHEN A DANGEROUS GOODS WAS DISCOVERED. OUTER BOX IS A PLASTIC PELICAN CASE CONTAINING MULTIPLE OFFICE SUPPLIES INCLUDING ONE X TEN OZ CAN OF INNOVERA DUSTER CLASSIFIED AS UN3159, REFRIGERANT GAS R134A. THE PACKAGE WAS FLOWN ON A UPS FLIGHT FROM GUAM TO DISCOVERY IN HONG KONG. THE TRACKING THERMAL LABEL DESCRIPTION IS FEMA EMERGENCY EQUIPMENT. INVOICE DESCRIPTION IS FEMA IMAT EQUIPMENT. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PELICAN CASE. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FORM GUAM USING UPS ACCOUNT 30250R, DHS FEMA REGION IX, 1111 BROADWAY, OAKLAND, CA 94607.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UPO experienced a UN3267 EDTA Acid Tetrasodium Salt 38% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. column168: DMP RECIEVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE FLOOR ON THE PD8 FROM THE DOCK SUPERVISOR WHICH WAS DISCOVERED BY THE PICKOFF. THE BELT WAS SHUT OFF AND SUCURED AND THE AREA WAS EVACUATED. A DESIGNATED RESPONDER DONNING THE CORRECT PPE RESPONDED TO THE AREA WITHIN 5 MINUTES AND USING THE DECISION TREE, IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND CONTAINED IT. THE OUTER CARTON OF THE PACKAGE WAS VISIBLY STAINED ON THE BOTTOM AND THE SIDES BUT NOT LEAKING OUTSIDE ONTO THE SURROUNDING AREA. THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING AND FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ONE OF THE INNER BLADDERS WAS PUNCTURED AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 12 OUNCES.

column168: While loading a pallet of lab pack containers onto a trailer at the Veolia 10 day intransit facility in Dayton, OH, a Veolia operator noticed an odor coming from the pallet. Initially, the employee did not see any damaged or wet boxes, so he proceeded to break down the pallet to inspect each box. After breaking down the pallet, a wet Questar box (141G) was discovered. Veolia estimates approximately one quart of liquid was released during the spill, most of which was absorbed by the fiber box. It appears that a bottle of allyl bromide broke in transit leading to the saturation of the box and release of liquid. The small amount of liquid that was released outside of the fiber box remained on the pallet under the box. The leaking box and spill pads used to clean up the spill were overpacked together for continued transportation to the final disposal facility.
column169: Veolia's safety manager will remind the team that when shipping a package containing inner containers of liquid material a sufficient amount of vermiculite or spill dry should be used to cushion the inner containers during transportation. The vermiculite or spill dry must be in a quantity that will be able to absorb the entire contents of the liquid material. The proper amount of cushioning should be used to ensure glass bottles do not break as a truck or trailer travels down the road.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced a battery acid release from a 2300-pound UN2794 battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of battery acid released impacting the trailer floor and an 8' x 30' area of concrete lot below due to the battery falling off a forklift. Absorbents and neutralizer were deployed and utilized to clean the released acid. The battery was decontaminated, the caps were re-secured, and the battery was secured for shipment on. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were containerized into a 55-gallon and 30-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On July 3, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of nitric acid had a loosened lid and released approximately one half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the site. Crews inspected the drum and suspected the seal on the lid was faulty. EWI utilized a forklift to place the drum into an over pack drum to be shipped back to the terminal for further evaluation. All released material was neutralized and recovered with absorbents. Impacted absorbents and PPE were placed into a poly liner and removed from the site for disposal.

column168: On July 4, 2023, one (1) 25-pound bag of Jack's Professional 20-10-20 General Purpose (UN1477) that was damaged due to improper securement during loading. As a result, approximately one (1) pound of product was released to the trailer floor and surrounding cargo. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services, Inc. (HES) to remediate the impacted surface. Crews utilized hand tools to collect and containerize all free-standing product. All undamaged cargo was inspected and repalletized for continued processing and shipping by the facility. The collected product, all UN1477-impacted materials, and the one (1) damaged bag were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. The drum was properly labeled and possession of the waste was retained by RLC for disposal through their bulk waste stream

On July 17, 2023, at 1947 ET, XPO Logistics terminal LTU suffered a cargo related release of UN1170 “Steol CS-460 Plus” from a 275-gallon poly tote, impacting the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup.  On July 17, 2023, at 2341 ET, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-gallons of product released to a 5' x 10' area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Oil Dri was deployed and utilized to clean the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and placed into a 55-gallon metal drum along with all cleanup debris and impacted absorbents. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SUPERVISOR CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE AREA, UTILIZED DECISIN TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. RESPONDER CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. RESPONDER USED SODIUM BICARBONATE   ZEP ZORBENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL, SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT,   PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. RESPONDER THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN RESPONDER OPENED THE BOX, FOUND THAT 1 GLASS BOTTLE WAS BROKEN   HAD SOILED THE REMAINING BOTTLES.

On 7/11/2023 at approximately 1525, Dangerous Goods Adminstration received a call from Employee 780470 at international hub in Köln, Germany, reporting a flammable liquid spill.  The shipment consisted of 8 fiberboad boxes, each with one metal can inside.  One of the shipments was discovered to have leaked onto one other shipment.  The cause of the spillage was undetermined. German policy on spills requires a call to the fire brigade, who then took possession of the both the leaking package and the affected pakcage.

Package was offered to a spill clean up specialist located at our Memphis Hub location.  During night time sort operations, ULD was opened to find a puddle under a large package.  Package had fibreboard strapped to a pallet and labeled as an overpack.  This over pack was covering 2 blue plastic drum containing 200 L of product.  It was seen that during travel, a small hole developed on the bottom of one of the drums allowing for an estimated 3L of product to escape.  It is not known when or how the hole developed.  Hole was patched before drum was placed in a salvage drum. and shipper contacted for an amended shipper's declaration.

column168: On 07/16/2023, at 1720 hours, personnel in the CSX Florence Yard (Florence, SC) discovered DAKX 29917, a loaded tank car of Ethylene Glycol, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Sabic, was notified (CHEMTREC Report 2023-0716-00035). HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found liquid product to be leaking between the liquid line valve mounting flange and the car’s pressure plate.  Contractor personnel vented the car’s pressure to stop the release. The issue identified and containment measures were communicated to Sabic’s representative- Greg Horton (Greg.Horton2@Sabic.com, 812-305-2295).  The car was held at the CSX Florence Yard pending additional repair and qualification or OTMA.

column168: During off loading, technicians at the receiving facility observed a cubic yard fiberboard container of hazardous debris was smoldering. The debris was contaminated with acetone and methyl ethyl ketone. The technicians isolated the container to an area of the receiving pad and extinguished with an ABC extinguisher. The contents were repacked to a new container and dry ice was added. The repackaged material was scanned with an RFID camera and determined not to have an elevated temperature.  While unloading the remaining containers of debris, technicians found that a drum of methyl methacrylate had partially released some of its contents. The material solidified as expanded foam. The solidified material was repackaged and sampled for analysis. All containers on the trailer were imaged with RFID camera and found to not exhibit elevated temperatures.   No materials were released.
column169: The incident is in investigation. The generator is implementing corrective actions.

column168: On 7/7/2023, at 11:00 am driver prepared to deliver Sodium Bisulfite 38% - NaHS03.The driver pulled the hose out from the hose reel. During the initial hook up to the customers tank with the pump engaged, the connection between the hose reel and hose assembly began leaking in the reel box, causing a release of product on the ground. After shutting down the system, the customer immediately was informed and they were able to contain the product from all ditches and drains, then used an on-site vacuum truck to collect the spill. The driver informed his supervisor, the supervisor informed his manager. The amount of the spill was approximately 55 gallons. There was no exposure to any of the customer employees or Univar employee. There were no injuries

column168: Lone Star Hazmat Response was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 5ft-by-5ft area of the trailer floor and a 2ft-by-2ft area of asphalt yard.  Lone Star Hazmat Response personnel estimated that  five (5) gallons of material was released due to  loose caps on almost  all the 1-gallon plastic jugs on the pallet. Lone Star Hazmat Response personnel removed all the plastic jugs from the cardboard packaging and verified that all the  jugs were impacted from the pallet.  Lone Star Hazmat Response deployed Sodium Bicarbonate to neutralize the impacted areas and then placed down Oil Dri as an absorbent. The spent material was gathered and placed into two 55-gallon poly drums along with the impacted cardboard. The impacted 1-gallon plastic jugs were containerized into two 95-gallon poly drums and two (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was labeled and staged in a secure location onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: While loading the IBC into a van trailer, a Veolia operator noticed the IBC had leaked nearly a gallon of waste on to the ground. The leak appeared to be coming from a outlet on the bottom of the valve. The valve would have to fail for this to happen. The outlet was plugged with spill pads temporarily to contain the leak and the waste was transferred in to another tote for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column169: Veolia will retrain personnel on container inspection prior to shipment from the customer. However, please note,  the valve did not fail until it was on the dock at Veolia 10 day intransit facility in Baytown, TX. There was no failure of the tote while the package was in public transportation. The Veolia crew who picked up the package from the shipper would have never known the valve was going to fail but the container did appear to be aged.

column168: A Memphis spill agent was called to the Dangerous goods building for a leaking package. The spill agent was told that the package was dropped during the unloading process. Inside of the fiberboard box was a single metal can inside of a plastic bag with paper for dunnage. The top chime was dented on the metal can causing the lid to open and the contents to spill out. The package was placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be obtained for movement.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XLA experienced a UN1197 Caramel Flavoring release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of product released impacting a 1' x 1' area of the concrete dock floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The product was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into a 55-gallon poly drum and one cubic yard box. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On July 7, 2023, three (3) 5-gallon pails of acetone were dropped due to mishandling and released approximately seven (7) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted surface. TLE noted that the material had hardened to the dock floor. The crew utilized acetone and hand tools to removed the product from the dock floor. All damaged pails, impacted absorbents, and product were contained in two (2) 35-gallon drums of waste. Following approval from the onsite contact, TLE secured the waste for delivery to the R+L terminal in Wilmington.

column168: On July 12, 2023, FRA Hazmat Inspector observed the protective housing securement pin not properly installed. Upon closer inspection, the protective housing was opened to inspect securement, the vapor valve was observed in the partially opened position. The camlock caps for vapor and liquid valve were not installed. The FRA notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer.  The CN Dangerous Goods Officer responded. Upon arrival, he also observed the protective housing pin not properly secured. Upon closer inspection, the vapor line valve was partially opened and the camlock caps were not installed. The Dangerous Goods Officer also noticed the AR placard was missing. The vapor valve was closed. The camlock caps for the vapor and liquid valves were installed. The placard on the AR side was replaced.  The railcar was released onto destination.

column168: On 07/23/2023, at 0924, CSXT personnel in the Avon Yard discovered ICCX74001, a residue Covered Hopper car last contained NA3077, Hazardous Waste Solid, N.O.S. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a slow leak from the bottom outlet flange at the bottom of the chute. Contractor personnel secured the outlet flange by tightening the flange bolts tool tight and decontaminating the impacted area. The leak was secured and the car was released back into transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 not required.

column168: On 07/14/23 at 1912hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal East St Louis, ILL Terminal discovered APHU659439, a freight container of "Freight All Kinds" with interior explosion and fire. The Fairmont City, IL fire department responded and extinguished the fire- no injuries were reported and no waterways impacted. Upon opening of the container, it was determined the lading included a hazardous commodity that was not described on the shipper's bill-of-lading; (UN3480, Lithium-Ion Batteries, Class 9, PG II). There were no indications of a hazardous material shipment on shipper's bill-of-lading or the freight container.   CSXT emergency response contractor, ENVIROSERVE, was dispatched to the scene for cleanup after scene was released by the fire dept.  The response contractor decontaminated all impacted areas and separated damaged lading into one roll-off unit.  All damaged freight was transported to the customer’s facility for further handling.   In addition to the shipment containing an undeclared hazardous materials, the cause of the fire/explsoin was due to inadequate blocking and bracing of the lading inside the container.  This allowed the lading to rub against itself, creating arc-friction, resulting in an explosion with fire.  The rail shipper, CMA-CGM America LLC, representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service, Case 672321.   The Illinois EMA was notified, report# H-2023-0587.

column168: On July 13, 2023, one (1) 446-gallon tote containing isopropanol experienced a faulty valve and released approximately one-half (.5) gallon of product to the concrete. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Miller Environmental Group (MEG) to remediate the impacted surface. Crews utilized absorbent pads to remove residual products and insure cleaning of the impacted tote. Poly sheeting was placed around the tote as a precautionary measure. Upon further inspection of the value it was determined that a part would need to be order to repair the tote. Crews transferred the contents of the tote into nine (9) 55-gallon drums to be collected the following day. All spent absorbents, damaged pails, and impacted cardboard box were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly bag for transport and disposal. After receiving approval from on-site RLC representative, Mr. Eric Tisdale, MEG crews secured the site and scheduled their return at a later date to replace the valve and transfer the contents of the tote.

SequenceEvent: The box was found wet in the load and moved to the hazmat cage for reports. SequenceEvent: Package was found in the load side wet, upon inspection contents were found having a loosed cap and about 1 liter having leaked out. Leak was mainly contained to box, remaining contents absorbed with absorbent pads. Package was loaded into a damage tote lined with plastic bag. DescribePack: Cap was loosened. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed on top of absorbent pads, though most was contained to outer box.

SequenceEvent: Package was found wet in load 2 after being dropped off by the tugger. Package had Corrosive HazMat labeling and was determined to be a HazMat. One of the packages corners was wet and leaking. Package was immediately taken out of the load areas and isolated from the rest of the staff. DescribePack: All 4 of the bottle's caps were taped down, in what seems to be an attempt to fix the leak. However, this did not work, and 2 of the 4 bottles began leaking out of their caps. The seals to each of the items were faulty and did not prevent any leakage. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Package was taken to the HazMat cage for isolation and processing.

Shipping label indicates that this box contains "1 gallon finished floor cleaner," a different (and non-hazmat) product than the disinfecting bathroom cleaner shipped in the box. column168: SequenceEvent: The package was unloaded from the trailer and placed on the ground. Was informed by the manager who opened the trailer door that it smelled very strong as soon as he lifted the door.  He noticed the hazmat package right then and notified QA personnel immediately. The hazmat package was slightly leaking so it was placed in a hazardous materials tote and taken to the hazmat processing area for further inspection. Spill was very miniscule as the fiberboard absorbed majority of the liquid. DescribePack: The outside of the package is labeled "CONTAINS 12 - 1 LITERS" but inside the package were only 4 - 1 Liter plastic bottles with no other packaging material to prevent movement. The amount of empty space and room for bottles to move about during transit caused a lid on one of the 1-Liter bottles to open, resulting in 1/2 liter spill from the inside of the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The manager who lifted the trailer door and unloaded the package immediately let QA personnel know and put the strong smelling package in a tote away from the area. The trailer was checked for any further spillage and QA personnel took the hazmat to the hazmat processing area right away so the smell would not negatively affect the package handlers who would soon be unloading the trailer.

SequenceEvent: At the beginning of the sort this package came out of a trailer during unload and was placed on a spill tray until QA could retrieve it. When QA retrieved it they put on nitrile gloves, and placed the damaged item in 2 plastic non-haz bags and then into a lined bin. QA took the time to look around the area for any residue to clean it up off the surface(s). Using a cart the damaged package was wheeled over to the QA station in unload. DescribePack: Due to leaks from the items inside the outer box got wet and due to the corrosive nature of the cleaner a hole was created on the side of the package about the size of 2 fists. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The manager in the unload put the damaged box onto a spill tray and QA used non-haz bags and also put it into a lined bin for good measure. QA also went a bit further and inspected the surrounding area where the package came out of from the trailer as well as around the spill tray to soak/clean up any remaining residue.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was unloaded from trailer and placed on the rollers. Package handler did not notify management hazmat had internal leak. ( Package handler may have been un aware.) Package was moved from 1 set of rollers to a second set. I was told package had spilled out onto a Package handlers shirt and his stomach is now irritated. SCMS was entered on package handler and hazmat was taken to hazmat area where was placed into a hazmat bag and spill bin. DescribePack: Hazmat states it has venting caps on product and that product is placed inside a small bag and then packaged into box with packing material ( Fiberboard Liners) package must have been loaded sideways at some point in transit because the leaking from the vent cap. Eventually pressure caused plastic bag to burst and material to leak out of plastic bag and cause internal leak and then eventually leaking onto package handlers shirt. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Once discovered package was taken to hazmat cage and placed into hazmat bag and spill bin.

SequenceEvent: Package came off trailer 568921 from the unload already wet leaking and damaged. Package was placed in a lined red tote and taken to the hazmat cage for inspection. Upon inspecting the inner contents there were 4 x 1 gallon   plastic bottles of Foam Brite Condenser Coil Cleaner. The 1 x 1 gallon plastic bottle had a loose cap allowing .20  gallons to release. Corrugated liner was on the top of the bottles and a liner was separating the bottles inside box.  No other absorbent was found. Facility procedures for damaged hazardous materials followed, contents  contained and awaiting disposition. DescribePack: The 1 x 1 gallon plastic bottle of Foam Brite Condenser Coil Cleaner had a loose cap allowing .20 gallons to  release. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a lined red tote to contain the damaged leaking package, taken to the hazmat cage for  further inspection.

SequenceEvent: Wet, damaged package was unloaded from trailer and immediately removed from workflow. Package was placed in a plastic tote and retrieved by QA member in Unload area for inspection. column168: SequenceEvent: Package was scanned to work area 141 at 9:43 am on 07/17/2023. Then at 12:01 pm It was scanned code 10 (inspection required). Package was left at QA1 in a plastic bag with the package covered in white paint. When QA arrived in the morning and began to process packages left at QA1 the packages was found in the damaged package area. Upon closer inspection it was found that the package was a HazMat. Package was placed in salvage drum secured to be processed post sort. DescribePack: Inside the package was found 4 x 1 gallon paint cans. All 4 were dented, soiled/stained in white paint, and 1 had its top come off and was empty. 90% of the interior of the package was coated in paint. Approximately 60% of the exterior of package was coated in white paint. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: The package was found inside of a clear plastic bag at QA1 damaged package area. Then placed in a salvage drum by QA when it was discovered that it was a HazMat. After which it was secured to be processed post sort.

column168: SequenceEvent: Found the package in a red hazardous material bin. I did not see any visible damage to the box. There was a strong odor coming from the box. I grabbed my PPE to inspect the box. There weren't any wet spots inside of the box. The bottles were packed in individual zip lock bags with absorbents inside separated by corrugated liners inside a big plastic bag. DescribePack: Three bottles' cap were barely on the bottle. Noticed there is a size difference of the bottle opening and the cap. The only thing that were keeping the caps on the bottles were black tape. The gasoline from each bottle spilled into the zip lock bag of absorbent. DurationRel: 12 and MitigateEffect: Kept the bottle upright and placed into a drum to control the odor.

column168: SequenceEvent: NASH admin discovered a leaking fiberboard box on the flexslide. Admin did not initially suspect this was a hazardous material as there were no diamond labels or hazmat paperwork attached to the packaging. Gloves were donned and package with all absorbed spillage was placed in a double-lined tote/bin and transported to the HMPA for further investigation. Pictures of the original packaging were found on Spidr.     The shipper TRU VALUE/PROMAX could not verify the presence of a hazmat or whether content was (as stated on original packaging) six 1 gallon plastic bottles of Rooto 10% Ammonia; their SDS service through Ambipar could not provide any details of Section 14 of the SDS provided. In the shipper's SDS Section 14, all descriptors (except for PG: III) were listed as NA. The manufacturer Rooto Corp provided admin with an SDS Section 14 that described the material as UN2672, Ammonia solution, 8 III. PGH was kept informed of all developments.     As the shipper could not verify content or presence of a hazmat, ERTS was called to verify the material and transfer all spillage to a drum. Constant ventilation was provided during this process. DescribePack: One of six 1gal bottles lost 0.7 gallon due to a loose cap closure. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: PPE was donned. The package and all spillage was placed in a double-lined, lidded tote and moved under ventilation for further investigation.    As the shipper could not verify content or presence of a hazmat, ERTS was called to verify the material and transfer all spillage to a drum. Constant ventilation was provided during this process.

column168: On July 13, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2922 was punctured and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer interior and concrete below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Environmental (AE) to remediate the impacted surfaces. AE personnel deployed granular absorbent to the concrete and worked them in with hand tools, utilizing a degreasing agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product. Once all free product was collected, crews utilized a power washer to further remediate the surface and collected the rinsate in a vac-truck. All methylene chloride impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum and transported to the RLC terminal to be added to the facility waste stream.

column168: On July 13, 2023, one (1) 125-gallon tote of UN2428 was damaged due to improper bracing during transit and released approximately thirty (30) gallons of product to the gravel, trailer, and soil. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Enhanced Environmental & Emergency (E3) to remediate the impacted surfaces.  Crews deployed poly sheeting to the impacted area and diluted the product with water. E3 personnel transferred the contents of the tote using a gravity transfer into a new tote. The tote was properly label and repalletized for continued processing and shipping. Crews utilized absorbent pads to remove residual products and insure cleaning of the impacted cargo .A pressure washer was used to clean the outside of the trailer. All spent absorbents and impacted tote were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal

column168: On 7/25/2023, at approximately 1650 hours, personnel in the CSX Russell, KY Yard reported a suspect  Non-Accident Release involving PROX17502, a loaded tank car ofUN1830, Sulfuric Acid- reported to have product leaking from the top. The car was isolated and the shipper, Norflaco Sales Glencore Canada, was notified via CHEMTREC (report #2023-07-25-00337).  Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve in the fully open position and the secondary closure plug not installed.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Marie-France Rollin (1-450-567-2026, Marie-France.Rollin@glencore.ca). Contractor personnel closed the valve with the valve handle and installed the secondary closure plug tool tight. Contractor personnel then performed neutralization and decontamination of the impacted surfaces on the exterior top and sides of the tank car. The car was placed on hold in the yard pending final inspection by CSX Hazmat personnel. On 7/27/23 PROX17502 was inspected by CSX personnel and released for transportation.

column168: On July 18th, 2023 the CBTX 742401 was found leaking vapor pressure through the vacuum relief valve.  The leak was identified by ODOT Hazmat Inspector C Kuenzi.  The car was isolated for safe inspection by a BNSF contractor.  Inspection confirmed that vapor was releasing through the VRV.  Responders attempted to vent the car and remove the VRV to put a plug in its place to secure the release.  The threaded VRV was unable to be removed by responders.  In consultation with the shipper, it was determined to clean and purge the car and ship to shop for repair under an OTMA.  An inspection can be performed at that time to determine the cause of release through the VRV.  There was no cleanup as all vapor dissipated.  Release estimates are based upon observations of the responders.

1. X-2023080212 SequenceEvent: Package was removed from the IC conveyor belt onto the IC rollers in preparation for loading. The rollers did not have a stop/catch at the end so the bucket rolled off onto the floor and the lid popped loose, causing it to spill. The bucket was returned to an upright position and QA hazmat was called. Upon arrival the package was placed into a clear hazmat bag in a red hazmat tote and returned to the hazmat cage. Spill pads were laid down to prevent to any injuries. DescribePack: The bucket was dropped onto its side and the lid popped open. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The bucket was returned to an upright position and QA hazmat was called. Upon arrival the package was placed into a clear hazmat bag in a red hazmat tote and returned to the hazmat cage. Spill pads were laid down to prevent to any injuries.   2. SequenceEvent: Contents was brought to QA, upon inspection, opening the content in a repack FedEx box. there were 4 jugs of Just Right Heavy Duty Degreaser. 3 of the 4 jugs were in large ziploc bags, the 4th jug was not. Upon further inspection, a team member noticed that there was a slow leak on the bottom of 1 of the jugs, possibly punctured during transit. Before finding out it was a possible LQ, there were no labels indicating that it was Corrosive liquid or a hazmat on the repack box. DescribePack: The contents were originally packed in one large trash bag and inside was four individual plastic bags. the one that was punctured was no contained in a bag. the puncture was located at the bottom of the jug missing the product label. There was not much protection between the box and the jugs. They appeared to be just double bagged. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Contents was inspected, attempt to mitigate further leakage, by adding absorbent sheets on the bottom of the leaking jug, until dealt with properly.

column168: On July 19, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing sodium carbonate was damaged during transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer floor and asphalt roadway as well as the soil/gravel shoulder. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from The L&R Group (TLR) to remediate the impacted surfaces.  Crews placed the damaged 50-gallon drum in an 85-gallon over pack drum for disposal. TLR personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and asphalt and worked them in with hand tools. Crews utilized hand tools to collect the absorbents and impacted soil and gravel from the shoulder and placed in a 30-gallon drum for disposal. All sodium carbonate impacted material was containerized in one (1) 85-gallon drum and one (1) 30-gallon drum and sent with the truck to the Boise, ID RLC terminal.

column168: On 7/25/2023, personnel at CSX Russel, KY yard, reported UTLX671478, a loaded tank car of Xylenols, was observed leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and SASOL Chemicals was notified via CHEMTREC (report #2023-07-25-00337).  Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found (1) of (8) manway cover bolts less than tool tight.  The manway bolts were tightened tool tight and the released Xylenols was cleaned from the top of the car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to SASOL Chemicals representative Randy Shilling (832-783-6428, Randy.Shilling@us.sasol.com).  Delay in report submission due to online portal would not accept.

column168: On July 26, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1760 was crushed during transit and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted surface. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area. Once neutralization was confirmed with pH strips, crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. The undamaged cargo was wiped down and repalletized for continued processing and shipping. All UN1760 impacted materials and spent absorbents were collected and containerized into  two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: During off loading the warehouse crew accidentally put a forklift fork into one poly 5 gallon pails Lo pH Conditioner Blue Cherry (un2796) of 1.5 gallons of product.  Contractors were dispatched for the containment and cleanup of the release.  On 09/15/2023, filer amended description via e-mail to state:  "UN1760 “Extreme Shine Was & Clear Coat” was not released. A non-regulated product called “AAP Velocity Clear Coat Protectant” and a UN2796 Sulfuric Acid, 8, PGII “Lo pH Conditioner Blue Cherry” released each from 5-gallon poly pails. A combined 3-gallons of products released to the pallet and concrete dock due to forklift punctures to the pails. Each pail was collected into its own separate 55-gallon poly drums. Water and absorbents were then used to clean the impacted surfaces and then collected into a third 55-gallon poly drum.   There were 15 total containers of UN2796 Sulfuric Acid, 8, PGII “Lo pH Conditioner Blue Cherry” shipped with one damaged. All waste was left onsite at XPO’s terminal for personnel to manage."

column168: On July 28, 2023, one (1) 1-gallon bottle of sodium hydroxide was damaged and released all its contents to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from E3 to assess the release. E3 contained the remaining product in one (1) 55-gallon drum for consolidation. The crew deployed absorbents and neutralized the released material. All impacted absorbents, debris, and PPE were contained in a separate 55-gallon drum. Both drums were labeled and staged onsite to be profiled and disposed of by R+L.

column168: On July 28, 2023, one (1) 250-gallon tote of UN3266 leaked approximately ten (10) gallons of product due to a faulty valve. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES+ to remediate the impacted site. ES+ personnel deployed granular absorbents and a neutralizing agent to the impacted trailer and pavement and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums. Crews transferred the product from the 330-gallon tote into one (1) 250-gallon tote and two (2) 55-gallon drums.

All additional waste was contained in the same 55-gallon drum for disposal by R+L.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was inbound scan at 0412 on 7/25/2023 at Edin 0785 and placed under the rollers at unload door 6 since it was a misloaded package. At 0700 QA was working on packages in the unload and came across the Item. Outer packaging looked wet damaged, so contents were inspected. Upon inspection it was found that 1 of the inner items had a leak. Package was placed in a yellow salvage drum and secured at QA1 to be processed post sort. DescribePack: Outer package appears wet damaged at the bottom one third / base of the package at one side. Tape closing/securing the bottom of the package is only covering 1/4 of the closure. only 1 of the 4 inner containers appears to be undamaged. 2 items appear dented at their base but have no leak. One inner container is crushed/dented at its base and has leaked over 1/2 of its contents. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: As soon as QA found the package inspection was performed to identify the cause of the wet damage on the outer packaging. When it was found to be caused by the inner contents of the package, item was secured and placed in a yellow salvaged drum and taken to QA1.

column168: SequenceEvent: The package was found to be wet on the outer container. Package was found to be a hazardous and was place in a hazmat bag and tote and taken for inspection. Upon inspection we found one of the six bottles had a loose cap causing it to leak approx. 6.oz all clean up material was kept with package. DescribePack: One of the six bottles had a loose cap causing it to leak DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package and all clean up material was kept inside bag and tote.

SequenceEvent: The package was discovered during the unload sorting process at this station in the morning. the item was brought to the QA dept for further inspection. The outer package had no labels indicating haxardous materials were inside the package. An admin begun the normal inspection while lifting and handling the package and observed their was an inner package with corrosive labels. Immediately the Admin placed the item down and noticed her feet were beginning to feel a "burning sensation."  Another admin quickly placed appropriate PPE on and read the label for first aid instructions. A SDS was printed and the admin took measures to wash and the area and seek medical attention along with a manager who completed an incident report. The package was then processed approprately as a hazmat and the containment mitigated and processed. DescribePack: The package was wet and had open closures. Upon inspection the outer package was retaped and the inner package had labels indicating it was corrosive materials inside. The label itself was undeclared. There were 4 gallon plastic jugs of cleanser/degreaser. One jug was missing a cap causing it to leak throughout the package and had noticeably less quantity in the jug. The liquid had saturated the other 3 bottles in the package. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Once Identified as a hazmat the item was placed in a hazmat tote. The process of paperwork was immediately handled. The first aid practice for the substance was printed and the Admin quickly began first aid measures and sought medical attention.

SequenceEvent: PKG WAS BROUGHT TO QA AFTER THE SORT AND THE BOTTOM WAS WET. 1 OF THE BOTTLES BUSTED INSIDE THE BOX AND LEAKED OUT. UNSURE OF HOW BOTTLE BROKE AND NO OTHER INFO WAS GIVEN TO ME. PKG WAS THEN SECURED AND LATER PROCESSED AS DAMAGED. DescribePack: BOTTLE BROKE INSIDE. INNER PACKING SEEMED FINE. NO HOLES, CRACKS, OR ANYTHING TO SIGNALS THIS WAS A PACKAGING ISSUE. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PKG WAS PLACED IN A YELLOW HAZMAT DRUM AND TAKEN OFF THE SORT AND SECURED.

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: DESCRIPTION: A 40ft ocean container caught fire while in transit storage prior to loading at the CSX ramp in Norfolk, Virginia. The fire was caused by undeclared and improperly packaged Lithium Ion Batteries (EV Vehicle Batteries). The container was loaded at a facility in St Louis, Missouri, chosen by the shipper. However, the shipping documents provided by the shipper to Apex Logistics, declared the commodity as "Copper Flakes" and not dangerous goods. RESPONSE: Upon notification of the fire, Apex Logistics International LLC informed the steamship line CMA CGM that there could be undeclared dangerous goods in all the containers from this shipper. 24 containers from this shipper were in Norfolk, VA.  INVESTIGATION: A surveyor has inspected the containers, and out of the 24 containers, all 24 of them have been identified to contain some form of dangerous goods, specifically batteries either class 9 or class 8. Some of the containers, contained D/D/R Lithium Batteries that were correctly packed according to the 49 CFR, however at least 4 containers contained unpacked Recycled Lithium Batteries (EV Batteries).  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: Due to the severity and complexity of the incident, the shipper, Zhiyun Sports LLC, has authorized Apex Logistics International LLC to arrange the pickup, storage, and return of the containers. Apex Logistics has contracted a hazardous materials emergency service (Hepaco) to assist in the offloading and safe storage of these dangerous goods.
column169: Apex Logistics International is not the shipper, however the shipper has been made aware of the correct reference to packaging and preparation in accordance with the 49 CFR. In addition this shipper has been blacklisted from shipping with Apex Logistics International.  Apex will continue to develop its Know Your Customer (KYC) training, in order to better vet potential violators of the 49 CFR.  In addition, we will attempt to identify shippers and consignees related to the recycling business to reduce the likelihood of undeclared Battery Shipments.   There currently is an open investigation on this incident from the DOT.

column168: On 7/18/2023 a Veolia employee from the Kenmore, NY office was loading drums from a truck into a trailer at the Veolia, Kenmore, NY 10 day intransit facility. The leak occurred when the employee was moving the drums into the outbound trailer and the employee noticed that the drums were very old and liquid was coming out of two of them. The drums were only supposed to contain solid material.  It is assumed that a small amount of liquid got into the drums prior to pick up and they leaked when being transported from the pick up at the customer's site in Clay NY to the Veolia's office in Kenmore, NY. Less than a liter of liquid leaked out of both of the drums. Liquid was only observed on trailer right below drum and did not leak out of the vehicle.   The drums were overpacked into 85 gallon salvage drums, the spill was cleaned up, and the drums were transported to the ultimate disposal facility without further incident. The duration of release is anticipated to be less than 1 minute as the employee noticed the leak right away.
column169: On 7/18/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation indicated that there were multiple drums that were supposed to ship from the customer's site and many were rusty due to age. Veolia employees refused to transport several other drums offered by the customer and checked the drums that appeared to be safe ship. Unfortunately two of the drums did start to leak after being transported. The other drums were also rechecked to assure they would not leak.

column168: On 7/17/2023 a Veolia employee was loading drums from a trailer into another trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility. column169: On 7/17/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. SequenceEvent: The hazmat pkg was on a closure cart in the middle area by our chutes where the closures and misloads go. I had checked on the package earlier to see where it needed to go, and did not see any leaking around the package. Someone had grabbed the cart that the package was on, and put it on the rollers attached to the chute, and about 30 minutes later, I heard the manager call out that there was a leaking Hazmat. I ran over to the area, and the manager, a PH, and another QA were picking up the leaking, corrosive Hazmat with their bare hands, putting it into a tote, and making the package leak everywhere. I immediately told them to set the package down and to clear the area. I let them know that it was a corrosive liquid and that it could burn them. They had already set it on the tugger, and it was leaking all over the back of the tugger as well. They set it down, and I grabbed it, and put it on my QA cart. When I set it on the cart, the liquid splashed up on my arms and on my left leg (as I was wearing shorts), and it started burning my skin. I told them to immediately clear the area, go rinse their hands, and I took my cart to the QA area, and hurried to the Hazmat shower to start rinsing my arms and leg off. After I had rinsed off for about 8 to 10 mins, I then went back and got the tugger that had been leaked on, and took it to the QA area to put it out of order. I then took my QA cart to the Hazmat cage and put the damaged portion of the package into a lined salvage drum. DescribePack: Package failed due to a loose cap on one of the bottles of Warewashing Detergents. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: I went to the spill area, and put the chemical neutralizer onto the spilled liquid and then put the shredded absorbing material onto it as well. I put caution tape over the area, and the next morning, I pH tested several spots, as well as the spots on the tugger, and then put down more neutralizer as needed. I then waited until about 11:00a that morning to sweep up the neutralizer and absorbing material into a hazardous material bag, and place it into the salvage drum with the other damaged portion of the damaged package.

column168: At approximately 07:30 on Monday, July 31, 2023, a Basic Chemicals truck driver was delivering 31.25 Sodium Chlorite to a customer site (City of Concordia Water Treatment Plant) located in Concordia, MO. The driver positioned the tanker in the offload area, connected to the customer's piping system, and started the flow of product. The driver quickly walked inside the building where the customer tank is located to check the status of the tank and then walked back out of the building to monitor the offload process. Upon exiting the building the driver noticed that the customer's connection point had failed (PVC cam-lock fitting broke free from tank piping) and approximately 5-gallons of product had been spilled to the ground. The driver quickly shut down the offloading operation and notified customer site personnel who immediately contained and cleaned up the spill. No injuries or property damage occurred as a result of this spill.
column169: The City of Concordia Water Treatment Plant (Concordia, MO) was contacted by Occidental Technical Service personnel  to review an incident involving a Basic Chemical's trailer of Sodium Chlorite solution being delivered. The customer site superintendent reported that the fitting was original and had never been changed. Photos showed worn threads with excessive salt build up. Concordia is performing inspections of the piping and fittings and will replace any deficient couplings and fittings on the system. They are implementing a preventive maintenance program to visually inspect these fittings each time they are used and will be replacing them annually going forward. Per Occidental Technical Service procedures, a Safety Smart report was filed with corrective actions.

column168: ODOT Hazmat Inspector C. Kuenzi identified the SHQX 50612 as leaking vapor in the protective housing during an inspection at the PTRC - Lakeyard.  The car was isolated by PTRC employees and BNSF dispatched contract responders to inspect the car.  The responders found the vapor valve plug to be less than tool tight, easily moved by hand and the valve to be partially open.  The valve was fully closed and the leak was mitigated.  The plug was removed, inspected and had teflon tape applied.  The car was fully secured and inspected, then released back into transportation.  All released LPG dissipated and no clean up was necessary.  Estimated release volumes are only based upon a best estimate as observed by responders.
column169: The shipper should ensure that all fittings and closures are fully secured prior to releasing into transportation.(NAR:136)

column168: On 7-25-23: A driver inadvertently loaded Ammonia, Anhydrous (UN1005) into a storage tank designated for Propane (UN 1075). As part of the recovery and remediation, the storage tank offloaded into two tanker trailers (MC331 ). On 7-27-23, the pressure relief valve on one of the recovery tanker trailers released a mixture of Ammonia and Propane in to the atmosphere. The release was caused by an increase in pressure caused by an Exothermic Reaction between the two commodities. The valve reset, but an unknown quantity of product was lost. As a result, representatives from PHMSA, the Indiana Department of Environmental Management, Indiana State Police and independent response personnel developed a new and more timely recovery procedure (Liquid Flare). The remaining products were safely rendered safe and the incident was declared complete.  A copy of the report from the recovery/remediation company is attached. Risk Management of East Central Indiana LLC.  NOTE: The carrier responsible is LPG Logistics LLC USDOT# 3142354. LPG Logisitics is the Owner/Operator Branch of C Three Logistics LLC USDOT# 2961868. LPG Logistics is the responsible party; however, billing and information is handled by C Three Logistics.

7-11-23: At approx 2100 hrs, in Morgantown WV our truck / trailer carrying UN,2312, Phenol, Molten, 6.1, II was flagged down. A mist from the top of the tanker trailer had landed on a car following our TT; Due to the HM product, EMS was activated. Fire, Police and HM responded. There was an light odor of the product in the air. A check of a valve at the top of the tanker revealed that hit was not fully closed. The driver had performed a pre trip inspection and the valve was closed at that time. No product was exiting the tank at this time. The product, which is not under pressure, would only be able to exit that valve while ascending or descending inclines. On flat ground the product· would not be able to be released. The valve was secured by HM Responders. The tanker was allowed to complete the remainder of the trip ( Approx 1/2 mile) to be unloaded. Two passerbys claimed to be affected by the product. They were transported to a local hospital for observations, then released. C Three Logistics has contracted with a HM response cleanup operation to properly decontaminate the exterior of the affected motor vehicle.
column169: C Three Logistics will be communicating with and working with the shipper, in order to ensure that their loading operators and our drivers are aware of the importance of properly securing the valve and to ensure that the safety measures are properly adhered to. column168: On July 2, 2023 at approximately 7:15 PM, a Plains transport driver with a load of crude oil was traveling southbound on State Highway 42 in Gregg County, TX. At the intersection of Hwy 42 and Texaco Rd, a 2012 Nissan traveling east on Texaco Rd failed to stop at a stop sign and collided with Plains transport, causing the tank trailer to separate from the tractor and roll over into the ditch. Upon separation, the landing gear broke off and punctured a 3x3 inch hole in the trailer, at the 7 o'clock position if upright, but upon roll over, puncture was located at the 10 o'clock position.  As a result of the collision, 70 gallons of diesel from the transport fuel tank and approximately 2 gallons of hydraulic fluid, from the trailer hydraulic pump and lines, were released to the roadway and roadside ditch. The Plains vehicle and the other vehicle were non drivable and had to be towed from the scene. An absorbent was applied to the roadway to encapsulate the diesel and hydraulic fluid, then swept and contained in 55 gallon drums. The impacted roadside ditch has been excavated to remove impacted soil and manifested for disposal, in accordance with TCEQ clean-up criteria. . .  The Plains employee was injured and treated at a medical facility. Occupant of other vehicle perished at the scene.
column169: No recommendations or actions were taken, as not deemed necessary due to Plains following DOT guidelines and not at fault for this incident.

column168: Reported to be releasing vapor and green-yellow crust on the car.  Upon arrival a vapor cloud was present.  Upon further assessment and opening the housing cover, liquid was visibly releasing from between the valve and the 4-bolt flanged cover plate.  One bolt was missing a nut (found on the pressure plate), one nut was loose.  Crew attempted to tighten without stopping the leak.  The crew re-entered and loosened the flange, the leak did not worsen so the flange was removed.  Product was on top of the ball valve and was swirling.  The gasket had a depressed area and was changed out.  The flange was tightened, and the leak continued.  The liquid valve was cycled several times and the flange removed.  The product was no longer moving.  The gasket was flipped over, flange tightened, and the leak stopped.  Upon arrival of the shipper, the flange was removed, the product was removed off the ball valve, filled with water, and ensured the ball valve was secured with no releases.  No releases were observed, no liquid emitted from the ball valve.  A new Teflon gasket was installed, the flange resecured, and the car diverted back to origination.
column169: Ensure that the car is properly secured and ready for release into transportation.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: SequenceEvent: Large box wet with gasoline delivered to damages area DescribePack: This is a lawn mower return which leaked gasoline from its fuel tank. Tank lid missing, Outer box torn apart and wet with liquid. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package moved to Hazmat holding cage on skid, excess leakage absorbed with shop towels.

Part of a multi piece shipment, package was offered to a spill cleanup specialist at the Memphis Hub when staining indicated package was leaking.  Package was seen to be in a fibreboard box.  It was reported inside the fibreboard box there were 2 plastic jugs each containing 1 L of UN1245, Methyl Isobutyl Ketone.  During further investigation found a cap on one of the jugs was not tightly secured on the bottle and allowed for an estimated .125L to escape.  Styrofoam peanuts were used for dunnage.  There was no positive closure noted on the jugs.  Contents of the package were placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper contacted for amened shipper's declaration for continued travel.

column168: On 07/14/2023 at approxiamtely 1215, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 658069 at the hub facility in Memphis, reporting an declared toxic shipment.  The shipment conststed of 5 overpackaed pallets, covered in white shrinkwrap. The shrinkwrap on one of the pallets torn for an unknown reason, revealing a package that was marked  "UN 3249" and  labeled with a 6.1 hazard label.  This overpacked pallet contained hidden dangerous goods.  Dangerous Goods Administration instructed the location to hold the shipment for further investigation; however, miscommunications lead to the shipment proceeding in transmit internationally, along with the other 4 overpacked pallets.  Dangerous Goods Adminstrition has instructed the team to hold the shipment for furhter investigation.

column168: On 07/21/2023 at approximately 2115, Dangerous Goods Administration recieved a call from Employee 245975 at the hub facility in Memphis, reporting an alcohol spill.  The shipment was 54 fiberboard boxes overpacked on a pallet.  One of the boxes showed signs of liquid damage.  Further inspection reavealed that the bottle inside of the box had completely leaked, cause umknown  the damaged package was removed from the overpack and set for disposal and the remaining pieces of the shipment await an amended shipper's declaration for further disposition.
